    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ec90956839448a6c",
      "text": "What does effective collaboration look like? Delays are avoided, information shared proves to be useful and relevant, communications are direct without intermediaries, work and priorities are coordinated in an effective way, relevant knowledge spreads, and trust grows."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "69a04025791f5e0f",
      "text": "Usually, this means that collaboration is synchronous as in pair/mob/ensemble programming, that information is shared on a need-to-share basis, and that social interactions are free instead of following the reporting lines."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "63e7d75156494998",
      "text": "Do you start with chaos? You start where you are and in some case you proceed by subtraction and in others by addition. The following principle also suggests making things work in the team before focusing on cross-team collaboration. The previous principles 2 and 3 suggest making teams more autonomous and reducing the cases where cross-team collaboration is needed, making the problem order of magnitude smaller."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b629c67a55d69b48",
      "text": "How do you get people past the fear of letting things “emerge”? How do you get autonomy and buy-in from sr leads to allow experimentation? The work should start at the single team level trying to make things work there,  where those questions should find their answers for your organisation, before scaling. This is suggested by the following principle. And it also helps to learn how to balance quiet voices and dominant voices, how to manage big egos, how to develop more self-awareness, and to create for the team quality time to think.\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "155acab8f1feaf10",
      "text": "Collaboration patterns for doing the actual work (e.g. a User Story that has dependencies or requires the involvement of another team) can be staggered (with gaps in between), sequential, or parallel. Coordination can be done by exception (when a problem manifests itself) or on a permanent basis by teams' representatives, or by all team members. Priorities can be arbitrated and orchestrated externally, negotiated internally by the teams involved, or agreed upon collaboratively by all teams involved. It is the nature of the work and the ability of the teams that lead to a solution that is good. The way to find what works is described in section J of the [[Principle 7 - Scale experimenting-learning-adapting-evolving guided by Complexity, Lean and Agile]].\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6f9e4069cef7a953",
      "text": "For cross-team collaboration start minimal, add cross-team collaboration ceremonies only when needed, make attendance optional as much as possible, and encourage to take conversations offline whenever is convenient.\nDon’t create extra meetings for the sake of it. Scrum of scrum can be a very expensive way to start. Having staggered Stand-ups instead can, for example, be a minimal way to let people attend other teams' stand-ups on an ad-hoc basis, only when needed (e.g. due to a specific dependency in the current or coming Sprint/Iteration scope)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8cd581475f06dd18",
      "text": "Trying to ”manage” collaboration and its improvement directly is likely to lead to worse collaboration such as traditional Programme Management techniques. It is more effective to approach the problem in an oblique way, doing cross-team building as we do team-building. The team member that has good social skills, a tendency to look at the big picture, a good knowledge of the company and the code-base, and a view of the dependencies that the team is facing in the coming Sprints/Iterations can be the good cross-team facilitator that is needed or can work in pair with the appointed facilitator.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "92a1fd2c559933e0",
      "text": "# Comments from SPA 2021\n\nDue to people centrality, it becomes fundamental to cherish the passion, to let people drive the changes instead of being told to change, and to be aware of and take into account cultural and other differences.\n \nA minimum set of agreements (like a narrow stable interface and a communication protocol) are needed to allow different teams to communicate and coordinate and ultimately collaborate, among them and with the rest of the organisation, understanding each other.\n  \nThis lead to the tension between preserving the stability of the existing agreements and the flexibility to change them to fit specific needs and circumstances. This is discussed for example in the paper _Software Development and CSCW: Standardization and Flexibility in Large-Scale Agile Development_ [https://eprints.lancs.ac.uk/id/eprint/127062/ pdf].\n\nGood Agile teams deal with a similar tension in relation to the team's ways of working, and they deal with it defining a minimin (the emphasis goes on minimum) set of team's working agreements and evolving and adapting them (gradually, locally, bottom-up) for example using the _Retrospective_. A similar approach could be used for a set of teams and their collaboration.\n\nWhen the number of teams involved grows, the costs of local adaptations increase beyond the benefits making standard unfit solutions less expensive, leaving the organisation to choose between high costs or poor approaches. This is why limiting the number of teams that need to work together (so limiting the dependencies and de-scaling) becomes so important."
    }
